00:18:28,087 --> 00:18:29,816
Maybe...

260
00:18:29,922 --> 00:18:32,322
Maybe she'll feel it.

261
00:18:32,425 --> 00:18:34,393
- Kiss her.
- Yes.

262
00:18:50,676 --> 00:18:52,610
Thank you, Sebastian.

263
00:18:54,280 --> 00:18:56,305
<i>Where are you staying?</i>

264
00:18:56,415 --> 00:18:57,746
At a friend's place.

265
00:18:58,584 --> 00:19:00,518
<i>Why not stay with us?</i>

266
00:19:00,619 --> 00:19:05,056
I'll be fine at Frank's, so...

267
00:19:05,157 --> 00:19:06,681
But thanks anyway.

268
00:19:06,792 --> 00:19:08,157
Call us.

269
00:19:08,260 --> 00:19:10,057
Yes.

270
00:19:14,733 --> 00:19:16,325
<i>What did you do</i>

271
00:19:16,435 --> 00:19:21,498
while you were alone with that
defenseless woman in the dark?

272
00:19:21,607 --> 00:19:22,631
<i>What did I do?</i>

273
00:19:22,741 --> 00:19:24,902
Hold her hand?

274
00:19:25,010 --> 00:19:27,240
<i>Or... Where did you hold her?</i>

275
00:19:27,346 --> 00:19:30,873
That's so sick, Frank!

276
00:19:37,823 --> 00:19:41,259
Hello, Sebastian.

277
00:19:41,360 --> 00:19:43,089
My name is Irma.

278
00:19:44,063 --> 00:19:45,894
I've come to wash Julia.

279
00:19:45,998 --> 00:19:47,488
But you can wash her.

280
00:19:55,541 --> 00:20:01,946
It's her armpits and between her legs.

281
00:20:02,047 --> 00:20:06,848
And anywhere you can feel
she's burning.

282
00:20:07,186 --> 00:20:08,619
Call me if you need me.

283
00:20:28,207 --> 00:20:29,697
Sebastian?

284
00:20:29,808 --> 00:20:32,072
Julia.

285
00:20:32,177 --> 00:20:34,543
Sebastian.

286
00:20:39,218 --> 00:20:41,379
Are you mine?

287
00:20:41,987 --> 00:20:43,921
I have searched for you for ages.

288
00:20:46,725 --> 00:20:48,955
<i>Where have you been?</i>

289
00:20:50,996 --> 00:20:52,861
Round about.

290
00:20:54,033 --> 00:20:56,228
Have you come home now?

291
00:20:56,335 --> 00:20:57,893
Yes.

292
00:20:58,003 --> 00:21:01,131
Till death us do part.

293
00:21:01,974 --> 00:21:05,933
No. Nothing will part us.

294
00:21:06,045 --> 00:21:08,240
Not even death.

295
00:21:09,648 --> 00:21:12,776
Julia, who are you?

296
00:21:13,519 --> 00:21:15,817
<i>Where have you come from?</i>

297
00:21:16,288 --> 00:21:18,813
<i>Where have you come from?</i>

298
00:21:58,964 --> 00:22:03,025
<i>Why didn't I leave Julia right there?</i>

299
00:22:04,036 --> 00:22:07,995
<i>Perhaps because my life
was just too real.</i>

300
00:22:08,774 --> 00:22:12,335
<i>And Julia's was mysterious.</i>

301
00:22:13,379 --> 00:22:16,109
<i>Beautiful women and mystery.</i>

302
00:22:17,516 --> 00:22:19,313
<i>I expect that's what it was.</i>

303
00:22:20,085 --> 00:22:21,575
<i>I was curious.</i>

304
00:22:23,389 --> 00:22:25,983
<i>I was just curious.</i>

305
00:22:26,692 --> 00:22:28,660
<i>What are you doing?</i>

306
00:22:29,528 --> 00:22:32,691
- I'm from the scientific support unit.
- Ah, okay.

307
00:22:33,365 --> 00:22:37,358
You find loads of weird things
in people's cars.

308
00:22:37,469 --> 00:22:41,098
I once found a pair of shoes.
And I found a Teddy bear.

309
00:22:41,340 --> 00:22:44,741
And I once found
a whole tin of Coca Cola

310
00:22:44,843 --> 00:22:46,140
nobody had drunk from.

311
00:22:46,245 --> 00:22:51,410
I once found a dead cat in the trunk.
That was disgusting.

312
00:22:51,517 --> 00:22:52,848
Did you find anything
in the trunk of this one?

313
00:22:56,321 --> 00:22:59,347
Listen, it's important.

314
00:23:00,192 --> 00:23:01,318
Yes.

315
00:23:01,427 --> 00:23:03,088
- You did?
- Yes.

316
00:23:03,195 --> 00:23:05,186
<i>What?</i>

317
00:23:26,251 --> 00:23:28,082
<i>What did you say his name was?</i>

318
00:23:28,187 --> 00:23:30,917
Sebastian. Christersson.

319
00:23:31,023 --> 00:23:32,490
Sebastian Christersson.

320
00:23:33,525 --> 00:23:35,686
You'll have to go back to tell them.

321
00:23:38,897 --> 00:23:39,761
I... I'll just keep out of it.

322
00:23:41,867 --> 00:23:44,427
And bump into the whole bunch
of them one day?

323
00:23:44,536 --> 00:23:48,028
<i>With Mette and the kids?</i>

324
00:23:48,140 --> 00:23:50,734
<i>What do you reckon Mette
will say to that?</i>

325
00:23:59,118 --> 00:24:00,517
No.

326
00:24:00,619 --> 00:24:03,417
I'd better go back, hand them the case
and tell them the truth.

327
00:24:03,522 --> 00:24:05,820
Good thinking.

328
00:24:12,264 --> 00:24:13,856
<i>Dear Mr. And Mrs. Castlund.</i>

329
00:24:13,966 --> 00:24:17,231
<i>I have committed a crime.</i>

330
00:24:17,336 --> 00:24:21,204
<i>I came stomping in on you
like some clown in oversized shoes.</i>

331
00:24:21,306 --> 00:24:26,175
<i>You were in shock, and I hadn't
the guts to tell you the truth.</i>

332
00:24:26,545 --> 00:24:28,706
<i>I am not Sebastian.</i>

333
00:24:28,814 --> 00:24:31,408
<i>I saw Julia's crash.</i>

334
00:24:31,517 --> 00:24:33,644
<i>I wanted to see
how she was doing.</i>

335
00:24:33,752 --> 00:24:37,552
<i>I am a photographer
with the scientific support unit,</i>

336
00:24:37,656 --> 00:24:39,920
<i>and I found this case in her car.</i>

337
00:24:40,025 --> 00:24:44,086
<i>Forgive this stupid misunderstanding.</i>

338
00:24:44,196 --> 00:24:48,292
<i>I wish you all the best
at this difficult time.</i>

339
00:24:49,034 --> 00:24:50,729
<i>Yours truly, a friend.</i>

340
00:24:50,836 --> 00:24:53,031
Sebastian?

341
00:24:56,975 --> 00:24:58,875
Sebastian!

342
00:25:04,249 --> 00:25:06,740
Have you talked to the staff in IC?

343
00:25:06,852 --> 00:25:08,513
- No.
- You'll be so pleased.

344
00:25:08,620 --> 00:25:14,024
You'll be so, so pleased.

345
00:25:15,527 --> 00:25:18,553
Julia has come round.

346
00:25:37,449 --> 00:25:42,853
But the chances of it returning
are pretty good.

347
00:25:45,090 --> 00:25:48,821
Sebastian has arrived.

348
00:25:54,266 --> 00:25:56,063
Sebastian?

349
00:25:56,168 --> 00:25:59,069
Your Sebastian.

350
00:26:01,006 --> 00:26:05,500
<i>What are you talking about?</i>

351
00:26:05,611 --> 00:26:07,579
I don't know anyone
called Sebastian.

352
00:26:14,586 --> 00:26:16,884
Julia, have you a boyfriend?

353
00:26:20,726 --> 00:26:21,715
Sebastian...

354
00:26:22,761 --> 00:26:24,456
Julia...

355
00:26:24,563 --> 00:26:30,297
<i>We'll take it slowly one more time.
Let's try again.</i>

356
00:26:34,306 --> 00:26:35,398
This is Sebastian.

357
00:26:36,475 --> 00:26:39,342
Your boyfriend.
You met him in Asia.

358
00:26:39,444 --> 00:26:42,902
You spent nine months there.

359
00:26:43,015 --> 00:26:44,846
Oh, God!

360
00:26:47,686 --> 00:26:51,213
I'm sorry.

361
00:26:57,329 --> 00:27:00,526
I don't remember a thing.

362
00:27:32,431 --> 00:27:37,266
Julia, Julia, Julia...

363
00:27:42,641 --> 00:27:44,609
How are you feeling?

364
00:27:44,710 --> 00:27:46,644
I think it'd be best for us
to talk about this.

365
00:27:46,745 --> 00:27:48,508
- This is too stupid.
- Yes.

366
00:27:48,613 --> 00:27:50,740
I know what you're thinking.

367
00:27:50,849 --> 00:27:52,817
I talked to Dichmann.

368
00:27:52,918 --> 00:27:57,287
Julia may be in a wheelchair forever.

369
00:27:58,523 --> 00:27:59,888
Listen...

370
00:28:00,692 --> 00:28:03,286
...this is all...

371
00:28:03,395 --> 00:28:08,264
...a big misunderstanding.

372
00:28:12,137 --> 00:28:13,695
Here. I've signed it.

373
00:28:14,139 --> 00:28:15,731
Put any figure you want.

374
00:28:15,841 --> 00:28:19,709
- Money doesn't matter.
- Precisely.

375
00:28:19,811 --> 00:28:22,371
<i>What matters is helping Julia.</i>

376
00:28:24,149 --> 00:28:28,381
I'm employing you to help
my daughter.

377
00:28:28,487 --> 00:28:31,183
I'm buying a bit of your time.

378
00:28:32,824 --> 00:28:35,850
<i>What happens later is of no concern.</i>

379
00:28:37,229 --> 00:28:40,858
Give her a bit of love,
for God's sake.

380
00:28:43,402 --> 00:28:46,997
Look at her!
My daughter is a wreck.

381
00:28:47,105 --> 00:28:51,508
You can't back out now
when she needs your help.

382
00:28:52,677 --> 00:28:54,008
You can at least pretend.

383
00:28:56,448 --> 00:28:57,938
<i>Write 100,000.</i>

384
00:28:58,050 --> 00:29:00,712
<i>A million. Whatever.</i>

385
00:29:01,319 --> 00:29:06,052
I have known women who can
pretend to love for much less.

386
00:29:07,893 --> 00:29:12,387
If I told you I wasn't Sebastian...

387
00:29:16,635 --> 00:29:20,696
I'd call you a damned coward.

388
00:29:23,008 --> 00:29:25,977
I beg you!

389
00:29:27,079 --> 00:29:30,310
Sebastian?

390
00:29:30,415 --> 00:29:31,507
Julia wants to talk to you.

391
00:29:39,891 --> 00:29:42,860
Dichmann says
you're my best medicine.

392
00:29:42,961 --> 00:29:44,690
Oh?

393
00:29:46,565 --> 00:29:49,227
Have we known each other long?

394
00:29:49,868 --> 00:29:52,894
A few months.

395
00:29:53,705 --> 00:29:57,197
Dad says we phoned
from Cambodia.

396
00:29:58,343 --> 00:30:00,208
<i>Angkor Wat.</i>

397
00:30:01,146 --> 00:30:03,114
<i>What happened there?</i>

398
00:30:03,982 --> 00:30:05,916
<i>What happened?</i>

399
00:30:06,017 --> 00:30:08,212
How did we meet?

400
00:30:13,158 --> 00:30:15,649
There was a bonfire.

401
00:30:15,760 --> 00:30:16,522
It was evening.

402
00:30:19,564 --> 00:30:22,965
Huddles of people
gathering in the twilight

403
00:30:24,436 --> 00:30:26,597
getting to know each other.

404
00:30:27,038 --> 00:30:29,506
People from all over.

405
00:30:30,342 --> 00:30:31,900
<i>Was I alone?</i>

406
00:30:32,010 --> 00:30:34,308
Yes.

407
00:30:34,412 --> 00:30:35,674
And so were you?

408
00:30:36,481 --> 00:30:37,914
Yes.

409
00:30:39,050 --> 00:30:41,314
<i>What do you look like?</i>

410
00:30:41,853 --> 00:30:43,218
Ordinary.

411
00:30:45,991 --> 00:30:48,050
Tall or short?

412
00:30:48,760 --> 00:30:49,749
Dark or fair?

413
00:30:49,861 --> 00:30:50,885
Dark.

414
00:30:50,996 --> 00:30:53,123
Ordinary.

415
00:30:53,231 --> 00:30:54,994
I blend into the wall.

416
00:30:57,669 --> 00:31:00,160
<i>What happened?</i>

417
00:31:00,272 --> 00:31:03,207
You were on your own.

418
00:31:04,376 --> 00:31:06,344
<i>With a Danish flag
on your backpack.</i>

419
00:31:06,444 --> 00:31:09,208
I offered you a bottle of Chang.

420
00:31:10,248 --> 00:31:11,545
Chang?

421
00:31:12,050 --> 00:31:14,416
Yes, it's the local gnat piss.

422
00:31:17,189 --> 00:31:20,181
<i>Two Danes in Angkor Wat.</i>

423
00:31:20,292 --> 00:31:24,160
Some coincidence!

424
00:31:24,262 --> 00:31:27,561
Love at first sight.

425
00:31:27,666 --> 00:31:29,634
If you believe in that.

426
00:31:31,002 --> 00:31:32,526
<i>What do you do?</i>

427
00:31:32,637 --> 00:31:34,468
I'm a photographer.

428
00:31:35,106 --> 00:31:38,075
I travel around.
I take photographs.

429
00:31:38,176 --> 00:31:40,542
For what?

430
00:31:43,048 --> 00:31:45,482
National Geographic.

431
00:31:45,584 --> 00:31:47,449
Features. Bits and pieces.

432
00:31:47,552 --> 00:31:49,110
Do you love me?

433
00:31:59,564 --> 00:32:01,589
Of course I love you.

434
00:32:01,700 --> 00:32:03,190
You hesitated for too long.

435
00:32:05,537 --> 00:32:07,027
I don't love you.

436
00:32:08,373 --> 00:32:10,102
No.

437
00:32:11,676 --> 00:32:13,541
I don't fall in love.

438
00:32:15,547 --> 00:32:17,708
That's sad.

439
00:32:19,217 --> 00:32:22,345
I have always been terrified

440
00:32:22,454 --> 00:32:29,951
of a life of habit, appointments,
regular meals.

441
00:32:32,530 --> 00:32:34,760
I hate rituals.

442
00:32:36,401 --> 00:32:39,393
I don't want to be tied down.

443
00:32:41,806 --> 00:32:45,173
Can you imagine such a life?

444
00:32:45,510 --> 00:32:47,535
<i>What life?</i>

445
00:32:48,313 --> 00:32:51,544
Husband, wife, a home.

446
00:32:51,650 --> 00:32:55,108
Two screaming brats
and a miserable job.

447
00:32:55,220 --> 00:32:56,983
Television.

448
00:32:58,456 --> 00:33:00,720
Friends round for supper
on Saturdays.

449
00:33:00,825 --> 00:33:05,353
Regular days for sex
once the kids are in bed.

450
00:33:05,463 --> 00:33:07,363
No.

451
00:33:07,465 --> 00:33:09,956
I can't imagine it.

452
00:33:10,068 --> 00:33:12,502
It must be dreadful.

453
00:33:14,172 --> 00:33:16,299
Or absolutely wonderful.

454
00:33:21,446 --> 00:33:22,777
Everything so predictable.

455
00:33:22,881 --> 00:33:24,746
Still no Other Half, Frank?

456
00:33:24,849 --> 00:33:26,441
As far as I know.

457
00:33:27,419 --> 00:33:29,080
<i>What was our secret?</i>

458
00:33:29,187 --> 00:33:32,452
<i>Can I surprise you with a rum
and Cola or a gin and tonic?</i>

459
00:33:32,557 --> 00:33:34,024
<i>We could...</i>

460
00:33:34,125 --> 00:33:38,619
I'll have a rum and Coke
without the Coke.

461
00:33:40,465 --> 00:33:42,558
<i>We could see.</i>

462
00:33:43,401 --> 00:33:44,663
See?

463
00:33:45,670 --> 00:33:47,194
Feel things.

464
00:33:48,740 --> 00:33:52,198
<i>We were refugees
from a tiny country.</i>

465
00:33:52,310 --> 00:33:59,648
<i>We wanted to see a world far bigger
than coffee, herring and chatter.</i>

466
00:34:00,585 --> 00:34:05,215
<i>And you provoked me.
And I provoked you.</i>

467
00:34:05,857 --> 00:34:09,418
<i>We kept surprising each other.</i>

468
00:34:09,961 --> 00:34:12,088
Always another experiment.

469
00:34:12,797 --> 00:34:13,991
And always...

470
00:34:14,099 --> 00:34:16,533
...always love.

471
00:34:16,634 --> 00:34:17,760
<i>Sex?</i>

472
00:34:20,472 --> 00:34:22,838
Several times a day.

473
00:34:24,309 --> 00:34:25,241
Liar!

474
00:34:25,343 --> 00:34:27,436
No.

475
00:34:28,146 --> 00:34:28,771
Did I come?

476
00:34:29,414 --> 00:34:31,382
<i>What?</i>

477
00:34:31,483 --> 00:34:32,211
I can never come.

478
00:34:34,552 --> 00:34:35,951
You always came.

479
00:34:38,423 --> 00:34:40,891
Are you full of yourself of what?

480
00:34:41,459 --> 00:34:42,187
Pardon?

481
00:34:45,096 --> 00:34:49,897
Nice to see you.
Good of you to come.

482
00:34:50,001 --> 00:34:51,491
<i>We've just said that!</i>

483
00:34:51,603 --> 00:34:53,571
Thanks for asking us.

484
00:34:53,671 --> 00:34:55,662
Did you sleep well?

485
00:34:59,411 --> 00:35:01,072
<i>Well, it is nice to see you.</i>

486
00:35:02,547 --> 00:35:06,449
<i>Where did we go after Angkor Wat?</i>

487
00:35:06,551 --> 00:35:09,714
At the rate I am going, I reckon
we are soon going to run out of wine.

488
00:35:09,821 --> 00:35:11,345
<i>Where are the other bottles?</i>

489
00:35:11,456 --> 00:35:12,718
Polynesia.

490
00:35:13,458 --> 00:35:15,426
<i>What?</i>

491
00:35:15,527 --> 00:35:16,755
<i>What?</i>

492
00:35:17,061 --> 00:35:21,521
- Polynesia?
- That's a long way to go.

493
00:35:22,167 --> 00:35:23,225
Yes.

494
00:35:23,701 --> 00:35:25,601
I always wanted to see Polynesia.

495
00:35:27,038 --> 00:35:28,266
Are you ill?

496
00:35:34,279 --> 00:35:36,679
Had you heard that Carsten
and Henriette are splitting up too?

497
00:35:36,781 --> 00:35:38,646
He found a Pole. The bastard.

498
00:35:38,750 --> 00:35:39,739
Did she come cheap?

499
00:35:39,851 --> 00:35:44,413
Marriage is like a new car.

500
00:35:44,522 --> 00:35:48,083
You're thrilled when you drive it
off the forecourt; it's all shiny.

501
00:35:48,193 --> 00:35:51,685
Slowly you lose interest.
You don't wash it.

502
00:35:51,796 --> 00:35:53,058
You don't vacuum the mats.

503
00:35:53,164 --> 00:35:54,688
<i>We're thinking about a new car.</i>

504
00:35:54,799 --> 00:35:58,860
You leave an empty bottle
under a seat.

505
00:35:58,970 --> 00:36:01,871
The only thing you want
is a new one.

506
00:36:01,973 --> 00:36:03,736
If only you'd been regular.

507
00:36:03,842 --> 00:36:05,104
Just once a week.

508
00:36:05,210 --> 00:36:07,701
<i>1) Wash the car.</i>

509
00:36:07,812 --> 00:36:09,370
<i>2) Vacuum.</i>

510
00:36:09,481 --> 00:36:11,312
3) Run a damp cloth
round the interior.

511
00:36:11,416 --> 00:36:12,940
<i>4) Wash the hubs.</i>

512
00:36:13,051 --> 00:36:15,076
You'd always have a new car.

513
00:36:15,186 --> 00:36:17,347
He's down there all day long.

514
00:36:20,525 --> 00:36:23,688
Someone must have poisoned
my apple.

515
00:36:24,863 --> 00:36:30,130
You kissed me, and I woke up.

516
00:36:31,769 --> 00:36:32,963
<i>Want to try again?</i>

517
00:36:40,378 --> 00:36:43,939
My face is a wreck, isn't it?

518
00:36:44,582 --> 00:36:46,846
You are beautiful.

519
00:37:08,606 --> 00:37:11,131
I think you're feverish.

520
00:37:17,782 --> 00:37:19,340
I'm going out for a bit.

521
00:37:21,219 --> 00:37:22,117
<i>What?</i>

522
00:37:23,955 --> 00:37:25,217
I need some air.

523
00:37:25,323 --> 00:37:27,348
